        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to map the spatial distribution of CO(5-4) in a Compton-thick QSO at z=1.245. 

The availability of Herschel data assures a reliable shaping of the galaxy SED up to the sub-mm. We integrated the best-fit galaxy SED template (in the rest 8-1000 micron) and obtained the expected L'CO(1-0) by assuming the relation LFIR-L'CO for star-forming galaxies by Daddi et al. (2010). This choice is reasonable, since our target lie on the so called "main sequence" (Elbaz et al. 2010; Rodighiero et al. 2011) in the M*-SFR plane at z~1. In addition, from a visual inspection on HST images, our target does not show clear evidence for a possible on-going major merger. 

We obtained L'CO ~ 1.8 * 10^(10) K km/s pc^2. The integrated CO(1-0) flux was then derived by following Solomon &amp; Vanden Bout (2005), assuming a typical FWHM = 300km/s (Tacconi et al. 2013). 
We obtained:

integrated flux: S(CO) = 0.216 Jy km/s
peak flux density C0(1-0) = 0.72 mJy

Then we assumed the most conservative CO SLED among those calibrated on active star-forming galaxies (from Weiss et al. 2007). 
We obtained:

peak flux density: CO(5-4) = 10.12 mJy (BAND 6)


ANGULAR RESOLUTION
We ask for 0.2'' angular resolution to detect and resolve in different spatial elements the CO(5-4) line profile. Given the source size, we expect to resolve the line in about 9 spatial elements. 


SENSITIVITY
We propose observations of CO(5-4) in Band 6 (~256 GHz) with 0.2 arcsec angular resolution. We made use of the ALMA Observations Support Tool in order to derive the simulated CO(5-4) map of our target, by assuming that its optical image (from HST-ACS in I-band) is representative of the intrinsic CO(5-4) spatial distribution.
In section 1.5 of the Scientific Justification, we show that the CO(5-4) distribution, if assumed to be co-spatial with optical emission, is expected to be extended and distributed over 9 resolution elements. We made a convolution between the integrated CO(5-4) flux density (10.12 mJy) and the morphological line profile. The requested sensitivity is computed so as to detect with &gt;3sigma level the faintest and most extended CO(5-4) flux density component, entirely enclosing the area covered by the optical image. Under this appropriate assumption, we obtain:
faintest peak flux density: 0.6 mJy
required sensitivity: 0.2 mJy

Given the expected spatial CO profile, we expect to detect and resolve the line transition with increasing significance towards the centre, up to ~12 sigma.

SPECTRAL SETUP
The spectral configuration has been optimized to observe the CO(5-4) transition and to dedicate the other basebands to the detection of the continuum in band 6. The adopted bandwidth is the largest one in all basebands, while the effective bandwidth required for CO(5-4)  has been binned in channels of 85 km/s. This value has been tuned to save as best as possible the required observing time (not exceeding 50 minutes on-source), but preserving at the a &gt;3sigma detection of the faintest CO emission component.


CONTINUUM
By using the ALMA sensitivity calculator, we found the integrated continuum emission to be detectable at &gt;5sigma level over the entire galaxy size. This additional objective does not require further amount of observing time.

Standard calibrations are requested.

The estimated observing time for this science goal is 1.64 h (49 minutes on source), including calibrators and overhead.

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
