        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to detect the CO(2-1) line in a Compton-thick QSO at z=1.245. 

The availability of Herschel data assures a reliable shaping of the galaxy SED up to the sub-mm. We integrated the best-fit galaxy SED template (in the rest 8-1000 micron) and obtained the expected L'CO(1-0) by assuming the relation LFIR-L'CO for star-forming galaxies by Daddi et al. (2010). This choice is reasonable, since our target lie on the so called "main sequence" (Elbaz et al. 2010; Rodighiero et al. 2011) in the M*-SFR plane at z~1. In addition, from a visual inspection on HST images, our target does not show clear evidence for a possible on-going major merger. 

We obtained L'CO ~ 1.8 * 10^(10) K km/s pc^2. The integrated CO(1-0) flux was then derived by following Solomon &amp; Vanden Bout (2005), assuming a typical FWHM = 300km/s (Tacconi et al. 2013). 
We obtained:

integrated flux: S(CO) = 0.216 Jy km/s
peak flux density C0(1-0) = 0.72 mJy

Then we converted from CO(1-0) to CO(2-1) by assuming a reasonable value of 3, which is not significantly model-dependent. (see Weiss et al. 2007). We obtained:

peak flux density: CO(2-1)= 2.17 mJy (BAND 3)


ANGULAR RESOLUTION
We ask for 1 arcsec angular resolution, since we are only interested in the detection of the CO(2-1) line over the entire galaxy size.

SENSITIVITY:
Since our purpose is only to get a 5 sigma detection of the CO(2-1) line emission, the requested sensitivity is the following:
required sensitivity: 0.43 mJy


SPECTRAL SETUP
The adopted spectral resolution is equal to the representative bandwidth relative to the CO(2-1) line: about 90 km/s. Such value is reasonable for this science goal, since allows a 5 sigma detection fo the line profile, as well as to save as much observing time as possible.


CONTINUUM
By using the ALMA sensitivity calculator, we found that the integrated continuum emission is not detectable (&lt;1 sigma confidence level). However, given the fact that no relatively intense line fits with our correlation setup, we choose to keep our previous spectral setup and dedicate three basebands to the continuum in Band 3. This additional objective does not require further amount of observing time.

Standard calibrations are requested.

The estimated observing time for this science goal is 43 minutes (about 15 minutes on-source), including calibrators and overhead.

</prj:justificationText>
