    <prp:abstract>We propose CO(5-4) and CO(2-1) observations in Band 6 and Band 3, respectively, for a candidate Compton-thick QSO observed in the COSMOS field at z=1.245. Our target is not detected from deep Chandra X-ray observations, although it shows unambiguous evidence for the presence of a powerful, buried QSO from several panchromatic diagnostics of active galactic nucleus (AGN) activity. 

Our "pilot" object is likely crossing a key-phase of AGN/galaxy co-evolution, where both components get triggered by cold molecular gas and the AGN might be completely enshrouded in dense gas and dust clouds. ALMA spatial capabilities would be paramount to investigate the molecular gas properties and to understand whether the host gas density is consistent with the severe central column density as responsible for X-ray obscuration.

We ask for high-resolution (0.2 arcsec) imaging of CO(5-4) in Band 6 to assess the morphological distribution of cold molecular gas with S/N &gt; 3.
We ask for CO(2-1) observations in Band 3 to get a reliable estimate of the total molecular gas mass and density.

The requested observing time is 2.4 hours (including calibrations and overhead). 
</prp:abstract>
